ped to the Adriatic coast, where he and several thousand other Jewish refugees were protected by the army of Fascist Italy. After Italy’s surrender, he joined Tito’s Partisans, becoming an officer and army veterinarian, and rescued dozens of downed Allied airmen. In 1945, he fled Yugoslavia’s Communist regime and reached liberated southern Italy. In 1947, at the age of twenty-two, he emigrated to the United States. With unique personal photographs and documents supporting the text, this eyewitness narrative covers little-known topics and provides a revealing historical account of the period. The book helps clarify and render accessible the complexities and contradictions of conflict and genocide in wartime Yugoslavia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945). 0aJewsxBiographyxYugoslavia. 0aJewszYugoslaviavBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Hungarian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Jewish. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xBiographyxUnderground movementsxYugoslavia. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPersonal narratives, Hungarian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPersonal narratives, Jewish. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, Italian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xUnderground movementszYugoslaviavBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory: Holocaust Studies. 4aHistory: Jewish Studies. 4aLife Writing. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  aAdriatic Coast.  aFascist Italy.  aHitler.  aHolocaust.  aItalian forces.  aItaly in wartime.  aMussolini.  aNazis.  aSecond World War.  aTito's Partisans.  aWorld War II.  aYugoslavia in wartime.  adisplacement.  ajews in the war.1 aRochlitz, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package: